column1: everyone heals at a different pace. .
everyone heals in their own way. .
you do what you need to do to get right. if that means steering clear of certain people or places
column2: then do so. if you have to skip out on a few events or occasions
column3: so be it. you need to do what’s right for you to heal
column4: because feeling broken after narcissistic abuse is one of the hardest feelings you will encounter. sometimes it might feel worse than the abuse itself. but that’s ok
column6: but you must be selfish and take care of you. •

column1: 194068;instagram;2019-01-28 12:48:12;FALSE;"as we embark on our day to day adventures... so easily do our thoughts take us away. either into anxiety on what the future may hold for us or in our past with struggles that are still leaving us tangled.
today... and the past few days... i've tried to really just let the thoughts be. not giving so much importance to people or situations that are so out of my control.

column2: through a lot of patience and support and therapy is that... the more energy we put towards our thoughts... the harder it becomes to live in the present.

column1: i am beautifully designed to have survived my past in order to provide awareness and education to children and adults alike on some pretty heinous crimes against humanity - our children.
but first.... i have to love my little me and let her know that i've done all i can to bring this matter to a close.
hopefully this time... justice will prevail over law.

column1: it’s really hard to come to terms with the fact that nothing will come from my sexual assault case. it’s heartbreaking because i know a lot of the people around me have been through a similar situation and they have also had no luck with the justice system. it’s bullshit how people are still victim blaming and making others feel like shit for what they didn’t ask for and couldn’t control. it really gets to me and i wish people would understand that this is often a daily struggle on why it went the way it did and why i bothered to put in all this effort for it to get thrown back in my face.

the ptsd and trauma that has been left behind by this disgusting human has shaped me into the strong but still fearful person you see today. ptsd from sexual assault is a double punishment. your body was violated and your mind won’t let you heal or forget it. it’s so so important to get verbal consent from someone before proceeding. consent can be withdrawn at any time and needs to be respected. another thing that comes to my attention is people saying ‘why didn’t you report sooner?’ personally i was reluctant because of fear of retaliation and fear of everyone finding out and the judgement that may follow. i tried my hardest to put it out of my mind until it was there every single day and i couldn’t avoid it anymore. i shouldn’t have to be scared and to have to watch behind me when i walk and being on high alert every time i’m down the street.. i wish i didn’t have to worry about any of these things but because of the past
column2: i’m always hyper aware of everything going on. to any other beautiful souls who have been through sexual assault or any assault
column3: you are not what the person did to you. you are so important and strong

column1: 194122;instagram;2019-01-28 13:45:08;FALSE;"#oxforddictionary's #hindiword of the year ""#narishakti"" recognizes the #importance of #women #empowerment
oxford dictionary is easily the #world’s most trusted source of words
column2: phrases and texts. their word of the year announced annually is reflective of the conversations and ethos of the year that has gone past. at the zee #jaipur #literaturefestival that recently concluded at the diggi palace
column3: the oxford dictionary’s hindi word of the year was announced – “nari shakti”. derived from sanskrit
column4: the word 'nari' means women and 'shakti' means #power.

column1: the year #2018 was significant in many ways for #indianwomen – while on one hand the #metoo movement exploded in the country and brought several persons of prominence in various fields under the scanner for their alleged sexual misdemeanors
column2: on the other hand several important decisions were taken by apex bodies in the country to empower women – including banning the controversial practice of triple-talaq
column3: allowing women to participate in combat roles in the armed forces and lifting the ban on the entry of girls and women into the #sabarimalatemple in #kerala.

column1: an advisory panel of language experts including namita gokhale
column3: randhir thakur and saurabh dwivedi helped to choose this as the hindi word that defined most conversations in 2018. as a term
column4: “nari shakti” is very #powerful – it not only has a deep connect with the past where goddesses in the country have been depicted as strong
column6: but also carried the language into the future to help hindi-speaking women feel #empowered
column7: while recognising their rights and potential.

column1: while the nation is still applauding the women power on display at the republic day parade in new delhi
column2: this comes as a welcome #announcement for an #uplifting and #empowering year for women ahead.

in a 2007 interview with playboy magazine
column2: talk show host and self-styled provocateur @billmaher defended the pedophilic relationship between seattle-area schoolteacher mary kay letourneau and her 12-year-old male student

column1: when pressed on whether he thinks teachers should be able to have sex with their underage students and not go to jail
column2: maher replied that it should depend on whether the student is a boy or a girl. ""if a 28-year-old male teacher is screwing a 13-year-old girl
column4: he said. ""but with debra lafave [another teacher who had sex with a student] screwing her 14-year-old boy student
column5: the crime is that we didn’t get it on videotape. was he being taken advantage of? i wish i had been taken advantage of like that. what a memory she gave him!"" maher may have intended his comments as tongue-in-cheek — he's also a stand-up comedian — but the 2007 interview wasn't the only time he'd made such a statement. in a march 1998 episode of his abc talk show
column7: maher seemed similarly supportive of letourneau raping fualaau. ""[letourneau] is in jail because she is in love
column8: he said. ""that's how i view it ... basically
column9: they're having a family and they're keeping the mother in jail because she won't conform to what society feels should be the perfect american family."" conservative activist celeste greig
column10: a guest on maher's show during that episode
column11: retorted that letourneau was in fact raping fualaau. maher insisted that it wasn't rape. ""raped?"" he said. ""come on. she forced? how do you know? ... how can a woman rape a man?"" --------------------------------------------------

column1: we are infinitely happy to have yuko shimizu @yukoart as our next lw&d interview.  originally from tokyo and now based in new york
column2: yuko is a freelance illustrator and instructor at the school of visual arts. illustration is actually yuko’s second career. she says
column3: “i have an undergraduate degree in business (advertising and marketing)
column4: and had a corporate pr career in japan for 11 years before i quit
column6: and enrolled myself in sva to start a new career path… i always loved to draw
column7: and getting a stable corporate job never made me happy. around the age of 30
column8: i stopped and thought about whether it was really something i wanted to keep doing. the answer was no. so from there
column10: then made up my mind to try myself out in art. worked a few years more to save up enough money to move to ny and pay for four years of art school… and here i am!” her advice to other creatives: “i can’t speak for other industries
column11: but as a freelance illustrator mainly working in editorial
column13: i can’t stress enough: none of my clients ever care if you are a woman
column18: if you have phd or dropped out of high school… you are only judged by the images you create
column19: and that is really really liberating and a fantastic field to be working in.” yuko shimizu’s full interview is on our lw&d website listed in our profile above. #ladieswinedesign #yukoshimizu ✨🙌💥

column2: i was a magnet for drama...

column1: i was attacked on the street and assaulted
i was hit by a taxi
i was date raped..... i could go on- but i won't :) the thing is
column2: i kept feeling so sorry for myself and because of that
column3: those ""bad"" things kept on coming.  and even though i kept asking god why?!?! it wasn't because i was being punished-- it was because somehow i liked it.

column1: not in the sense that you ""like"" ice cream- but in the sense that i became comfortable with drama and stories that made people say ""oh my god""... and attention wasn't a bad thing either.
most people do not want to even consider that they could be welcoming in pain~ but it's true.
if we become comfortable with what happens as a result of it
column2: we are very good at keeping it coming and not even knowing that we're doing it.

column1: as soon as i learned this and stopped enjoying the drama and the victimhood life
column2: all those things stopped and my life became more ""good"" things happening and it's great!

column1: it's amazing what can happen when we recognize the power of familiarity and comfort--- we can find all the subconscious patterns we might be holding onto that aren't bringing us what we want.
i know because i did- and its kind of fun to ask yourself... is it possible i'm inviting some things into my life that i no longer need or want? and what becomes possible when i stop?
swapping ""bad"" things happening for ""good"" ones is always enjoyable. i promise!
what do you think about this? has this happened to you too? i'd love to know! .

column2: i was a magnet for drama...

column1: i was attacked on the street and assaulted
i was hit by a taxi
i was date raped..... i could go on- but i will not :) the thing is
column2: i kept feeling so sorry for myself and because of that
column3: those ""bad"" things kept on coming.  and even though i kept asking god why?!?! it wasn't because i was being punished-- it was because somehow i liked it.

column1: not in the sense that you ""like"" ice cream- but in the sense that i became comfoable with drama and stories that made people say ""oh my god""... and attention wasn't a bad thing either.
most people do not want to even consider that they could be welcoming in pain~ but it is true.
if we become comfoable with what happens as a result of it
column2: we are very good at keeping it coming and not even knowing that we're doing it.

column1: as soon as i learned this and stopped enjoying the drama and the victimhood life
column2: all those things stopped and my life became more ""good"" things happening and it is great!

column1: it is amazing what can happen when we recognize the power of familiarity and comfo--- we can find all the subconscious patterns we might be holding onto that are not bringing us what we want.
i know because i did- and its kind of fun to ask yourself... is it possible i am inviting some things into my life that i no longer need or want? and what becomes possible when i stop?
swapping ""bad"" things happening for ""good"" ones is always enjoyable. i promise!
what do you think about this? has this happened to you too? i'd love to know! .

column1: 194217;instagram;2019-01-28 15:30:51;FALSE;"i started this page because i had to start my life over. i got out of an abusive relationship and had to delete all my social media pages and leave my home. i started this instagram because i still wanted to share the little adventures in my life in a new town in a new apartment without anyone knowing who i am. i never show pictures of my face so that the person who made me start over can't find me again. 2018 was tough for me. and now 2019 has started with me lying in the hospital bed with my mother holding her hand as she finds out that her cancer has spread everywhere. she is the most amazing woman in the world and has been there for me through everything. it feels like more than i can bear. i know you don't know me and i normally just share little posts about my home but if you could spare a thought or a prayer for my mother it would mean the world to me.

column1: 194218;instagram;2019-01-28 15:31:25;FALSE;"women formed a 620km human chain for gender equality in kerala
column2: india. organisers estimate that three million women protested a ban on women of menstruating age approaching the hindu sabarimala temple. the deity lord ayyappa is celibate
column3: so traditionalists believe women under 50 should not enter the temple to offer prayers for fear that they could “tempt” him. despite india's supreme court overturning the ban in 2018
column4: some were denied entry to one of hinduism's holiest temples by conservative protestors. the ""women's wall"" protest was organised by the left-wing government in the southern indian state to make a stand against discrimination.

column1: 194280;instagram;2019-01-28 16:58:20;FALSE;"vi pratar mäns våld på forum jämställdhet 2019
den 30-31 januari kommer män att närvara vid forum jämställdhet 2019 i luleå. fj är sveriges största jämställdhetskonferens och lyfter många olika jämställdhetsfrågor.
på onsdagen deltar mäns ordförande alán ali i nedanstående panelsamtal:
incels – hur kan vi förstå dem?

på senare tid har ensamma män som hatar kvinnor börjat organisera sig och bekräfta varandras frustration på nätet. hur hänger hatet mot kvinnor ihop med rasism och hat mot andra grupper? hur kan vi förbygga
på torsdag håller män i en metodverkstad:

idag tar pappor ut en fjärdedel av föräldradagarna. den ojämna fördelningen upprätthåller ojämställdhet i familjen och arbetslivet. organisationen män ser också att risken för mäns våld mot kvinnor minskar när pappor delar ansvaret för barn och hem. för att uppmuntra män att ta ett större ansvar erbjuder organisationen pappagrupper och samtalsmaterial till pappor och utbildningar i jämställt föräldrastöd till vårdpersonal och andra som möter föräldrar.
utöver detta har vi en monter där du är välkommen att prata med oss
column3: ta med dig några av våra trycksaker som “en kommun fri från våld” och “men
column4: masculinity and #metoo” eller bara hänga. vi vill gärna träffa dig och prata med dig om hur vi kan engagera fler män för jämställdhet och mot våld! (för att kunna närvara vid konferensen

column1: ps. glöm inte att vi håller ett stormöte #eftermetoo med män luleå tisdag 29 januari. anmäl dig via länk i vår bio!";;en;#MeToo”

column3: the truth is there was not inconsistencies otherwise the courts would not have found us credible.  if there is one material inconsistency you are not found credible.  that's how it works. furthermore this is just an extremely insensitive comment and a complete disregard for her good buddy’s daughter

column1: we were devastated when we found out that she had heard the whole thing. we were so hopeful albeit naively that the children were not exposed to this violence. i worry about how this will manifest later for my own daughter.

ultimately it was shared with me by my stepdaughter that she knew it me screaming because she recognized my sounds having been at the natural birth of her little sister. i guess in giving life and trying to save your own you make similar sounds. primal sounds.

taking this to the courts and using it against us making it our fault her god daughter had to partially witness her mothers’ violence and trying to spin into us scheming conspiracy to steal this child from her mother is disgraceful.
grow up. had anyone else done this to me. a stranger

column1: we support @missm.justice and the @rapecrisisscotland end not proven campaign.

column3: not guilty and not proven. not guilty and not proven have the same impact – both are acquittals
column4: and there are no legal consequences for the accused if they get a not proven verdict.

column2: i was a juror on one of these cases. the case involved a man accused of multiple sexual assaults
column3: which resulted in our jury giving a not proven verdict. a majority of one went with a verdict of not proven. the rest of us said guilty. no one on the jury thought he was not guilty. not one person.

column1: at the time of the trial
column2: i didn't know if i could call myself a rape survivor. mainly because i'd internalised the myth that you can't be raped by someone you are in a relationship with.

column1: the case was a devastating and swift lesson in how little survivors are believed. how easily men are excused. again
column2: not one juror thought he was innocent. it was clear that it was more important to protect the perpetrator. the jury used not proven to this end. i can only imagine how awful this would have been for the survivors in the case. the experience also delayed me coming to terms with my own rape for years.

column1: the not proven verdict is used disproportionately in rape cases. nearly 30% of acquittals were not proven
column2: compared with 17% for all crimes and offences.

column1: the not proven verdict has the exact same impact as a not guilty verdict
column2: and can be just as distressing for the survivor.

column1: if you live in scotland please write to your msp about ending the not proven verdict. there's lots more info on the @rapecrisisscotland website.

column2: you have helped so many of your fellow survivors with your work. 🖤

column1: 194347;instagram;2019-01-28 18:11:56;FALSE;"i used to think it would never happen to me.

i used to think that women in abusive #relationships put themselves into that situation. i used to think they were dumb for not just leaving. i used to not understand why they were so scared to walk away. until i became that #woman. and i didn’t realize until it was way too late.
i used to think i needed someone that made me cry everyday. i used to obey all the demands that someone else asked of me
column2: even if they made me #uncomfortable. i used to be forced into situations that made me sick to my stomach as i was in them. i used to think i was #unworthy of love
column4: and success because i was a terrible person. i used to believe that i was so lucky to have found the one person in the world that would ever #love me because no one else could possibly love me. i used to be #abused.

column1: i don’t think that way anymore. i made it out and i’ve been #evolving into a better woman than i could have ever imagined. but when i look back at photos or videos of that terrible time
column2: i feel like i’m looking at a stranger. how did i allow myself to be abused?  because i was lost. i was #brainwashed. i was pushed down so many times that i had no #confidence or #hope. i was gradually lulled into a false sense of security before the #evil of my abuser came to the surface. i was brought up so high by this person and at the same time thrown into the dirt by them too.

column1: and now i understand why women find it hard to leave their #abuser. because it doesn’t just happen overnight. because it’s a sneaky manipulation. because you don’t realize it’s #abuse and that you are in this situation until you are finally outside of it
column2: looking in. but you can leave. you can make it out. you are #strong enough. if you or anyone you know is stuck in an #abusiverelationship
column3: please visit thehotline.org. and never hesitant to message me either. there are resources for you. you do not deserve this. you are deserving of love. #isurvived #domesticviolence #toxicrelationship #overcome #womensrights #metoo #timesup";;en;#relationships

column1: 194372;instagram;2019-01-28 18:43:33;TRUE;;"dema and i spent the last year in a sex love and relationship coaching training together. we’ve had many conversations about the dynamics between men and women. me
column2: with a focus for the last few years on coaching women into their power
column3: and dema now working with men. i really loved this conversation in particular. it was raw and flowing. as i’ve been dating a new man the last few months i’ve been thinking a lot about what it takes to actually relate with eachother as women and men in and out of the bedroom in a post #metoo conscious relationship. it’s given me so many insights
column4: and both strengthened and softened me in how i show up with men. romantically or otherwise. we also offer suggestions for what men can do to show up for us. do check it out. cw note: we do discuss some of our past experiences of assault. not graphic
column5: but content could potentially be triggering. #repost @demetra_nyx

column1: lesson 1: self-defense is a state of mind
much like defense against the dark arts
column2: self-defense requires constant vigilance! being aware of your surroundings is the first step in self-defense because you can't defend yourself from something you don't know is a threat. think of your personal bubble as a real
column3: physical thing. anyone within 10 feet of you could be a threat
column4: but anyone within 4 feet needs to be treated with caution. (there's no science behind these numbers. they're just my own personal gauge.) if you're already keeping an eye out for someone
column5: it's less shocking when they begin to invade your space: you half expected this anyway💁🏼‍♀️ from here
column6: there are a few simple steps for a basic defense move.

column1: 1. get your space: step one leg back
column2: put your hands up at your eye level with your palms facing out
column3: and vocalize to let them know you're aware of them. ""what's up?"" ""whoa"" ""can i help you?""

column1: 2. strike if you need to: if the person continues to approach
column2: it's time to strike. shove the webbing between your thumb and index finger into their throat or kick them in the shin or knee. - ""but what about the groin?"" if your knee comes high enough to hit them in the groin
column3: they will see it coming and be more likely to block.

column2: you should only use these techniques if you need to hurt someone to protect yourself. treat these as dangerous tools. that being said
column3: you should practice with them to become proficient. it will feel silly at first
column4: but find a friend who will practice with you. take turns being the aggressor. keep practicing until ""hands up
column5: step back"" is your first response. if you aren't practicing
column6: chances are your first response will be to freeze up.

column1: lesson 1: self-defense is a state of mind
much like defense against the dark arts
column2: self-defense requires constant vigilance! being aware of your surroundings is the first step in self-defense because you can't defend yourself from something you don't know is a threat. think of your personal bubble as a real
column3: physical thing. anyone within 10 feet of you could be a threat
column4: but anyone within 4 feet needs to be treated with caution. (there's no science behind these numbers. they're just my own personal gauge.) if you're already keeping an eye out for someone
column5: it's less shocking when they begin to invade your space: you half expected this anyway💁🏼‍♀️ from here
column6: there are a few simple steps for a basic defense move.

column1: 1. get your space: step one leg back
column2: put your hands up at your eye level with your palms facing out
column3: and vocalize to let them know you're aware of them. ""what's up?"" ""whoa"" ""can i help you?""

column1: 2. strike if you need to: if the person continues to approach
column2: it's time to strike. shove the webbing between your thumb and index finger into their throat or kick them in the shin or knee. - ""but what about the groin?"" if your knee comes high enough to hit them in the groin
column3: they will see it coming and be more likely to block.

column2: you should only use these techniques if you need to hurt someone to protect yourself. treat these as dangerous tools. that being said
column3: you should practice with them to become proficient. it will feel silly at first
column4: but find a friend who will practice with you. take turns being the aggressor. keep practicing until ""hands up
column5: step back"" is your first response. if you aren't practicing
column6: chances are your first response will be to freeze up.

column1: das ist unser abendritual.. jeden abend kommt unsere prinzessin ins bett und verpasst mir eine manchmal schmerzhafte kopfmassage aber es ist trotzdem schön wenn sie dann auf meinem kopf einschläft und vor sich hin schnurrt.. das hat sowas beruhigendes.
habt ihr auch rituale zum einschlafen?
jetzt zum wochenende 🙈 was war das schön aber auch verdammt anstrengend 😂

samstag habe ich mich nicht ganz an meinen ernährungsplan gehalten.. habe quasi einen cheatday eingelegt. ich habe #pulledpork selber gemacht und wir hatten unsere freunde @me_myself_and_i_1606 zu besuch. abends sind mein schatz @44653wan und ich mit nem guten freund feiern gegangen. es war unglaublich lustig aber ich muss ehrlich sagen ich war tot..🙈 der tag in klinik war heute mal wieder sehr aufwühlend und ich bin schon wieder an meine grenze gekommen. so therapieeinheiten bezüglich der beziehung zum eigenen körper sind echt harte arbeit für mich. aber die therapeutin ist zuversichtlich
column2: dass es sich bessern wird. ich hoffe es zumindest. denn dieses gefühl von angst bei berührungen ist echt anstrengend.

column1: morgen gibt es dann auch wieder eine andere art von körperarbeit. wir sind wieder zum einzeltraining beim @iliasessaoudiofficial ich bin mal gespannt wie hart der muskelkater diesmal sein wird.
ich wünsche euch einen wundervollen abend und eine ruhige nacht

column1: i was molested by michael shepherd at 11 years old
column3: and my god cousin. i trusted him and for years i felt like i let him do it and therefore he wasn’t guilty. i wanted him to keep saying i was his favorite
column5: to not leave me out like i felt my other cousins did. i was shy
column7: awkward and a target for him. recently
column8: i saw him with a fellow actor and their 9 year old daughter and physically i went back
column9: i had to speak up. that moment i did not. i ran out the room and cried. i was mad at myself and felt weak. i then got the courage to speak up. this was my first time sharing this with people outside of my mother and close friends. i did not want to argue and plead my case
column10: i did not know how close they were and i didn’t want to have to defend myself now especially when i failed to defend myself then. i did not want to go toe to toe with ignorance like people have been on social media about #muterkelly and #metoo.i felt powerless but i spoke up and thankfully i was heard. my associate assured me the daughter was never alone with him. they also let me know they would keep him from my presence and their daughters. •

column1: 194670;instagram;2019-01-29 00:43:04;FALSE;"i know. i didn't have time either.

column2: i felt like i barely kept my head above water. my family needed me in so many different ways
column4: there was no way i could make time for myself

column1: this mama felt anything but inspiring. or capable of anything outside the realm of momming. and she was just plain exhausted.
but i realized that if i didn't make time
column2: nothing would change. if i didn't do something different
column4: everything would still be the same
column5: or worse.  my well felt dry
column6: like it had nothing more to give.

column1: but when the well runs dry
i took a look at my day and counted up the minutes that kept me too busy. besides obvious parenting duties
column2: i spent my free time catching up on the dvr
column3: scrolling fb and insta a few dozen times a day
column4: pinterest was such a time sucker
column7: wishing i could get more sleep
column8: etc. not one of those free time activities was making me feel better
column9: they were just passing time. i could give up one 30 minute show or scroll 30 minutes less

column2: i actually decided to wake up earlier to start my fitness journey. this tired mom
column3: got less sleep that first week to be dedicated to  helping herself.
slept better in that shorter time
column7: rather than spinning out of it. i wanted to do those mindless things less because i was excited to do more.

column1: i learned to focus on nutrition
column2: surrounded myself with like-minded women on their journey
column3: realized that i loved fitness and helping others more than i ever would have realized. building a business out of it
column5: i still eat cake. but only if it's gluten free now)

column1: it was hard at first to temporarily give up some foods i swore i never would. but when i felt better and more comforted by health than with oreos
putting myself out there and sharing my journey was way out of my comfort zone. but that also brought a certain thrill. and when others complimented or wanted to ""do what i was doing""

column1: for the last few months i’ve been working on this story about my 2018 journalism lecturer grant hannis. last week he got convicted of indecently assaulting an 82-year-old stroke victim and much of the coverage discussed how respected he was as a teacher. however in the herald
column2: we can reveal several women made complaints about hannis to the head of school that were not taken too seriously.

column1: finding this out in september was tough. by the end of my time in the course i had just stopped turning up to classes because i couldn’t be in the same room as him and was knotted in guilt at not being able to talk to my classmates for safety and legal reasons. please read and hear what this story has to say - writing this took all my courage and turned my bones to dust.

column1: 194739;instagram;2019-01-29 02:03:17;FALSE;"my favorite subject in school was always history.
being able to learn about what happened on this planet before i got here excited me
but never did i realize that i’m living history.
that the past was once the present.
from the moment i was born i’ve been making my own personal history
my life has been a series of personal wars and victories

column2: i have been working on my website blog project for women for several weeks now and its ready to release finally!! 👏👏 after being single for 5 years and moving back to america i was ready for a committed relationship and have someone special in my life. after a 1 year and 4 month relationship of being cheated on and habitually lied to by a man who had multiple addictions
column3: i realized i was overlooking so many things and that i was rusty at being a master observer. there were so many signs and red flags as well as my gut instincts that i put aside because i did not want to believe.

column1: having suffered sexual abuse by a pedophile and mental and physical abuse by a psychopath/emotionally unstable person at age 5 until 11
column4: i can tell you i am now a master observer!!! i have become extremely educated in toxic personality types and have created a website and video blog to educate women on learning how to be a master observer of toxic people and dangerous personality types such as a narcissist
column6: psychopath and predator. my video blog www.safespaceforyou.weebly.com has joined forces with the woman's community hotline and healthy place to offer resources from domestic abuse to mental illness. i feel it is my duty to educate
column7: support and fight for those women who need help and guidance. you are not alone and together we can overcome anything with the correct information
column8: resources and compassion it takes to walk away from any toxic relationship.

column1: he pushed me into the bedroom
column3: and threw onto the bed. he jumped on top of me and i immediately felt my heart sink thinking i was about to be violated against my will. it wouldn’t have been the first time. •

column1: there was a bit of a struggle and then he screamed that i was making him do this. thankfully he jumped off of me. he pulled me up and left the room and came back in with a six inch butcher knife. he put it in my face and told me again that this was my fault. that i was making him do this. he then stabbed the door next to my head and started pacing the apartment muttering about how much of a tease i was and telling me it was all my fault. he eventually went outside and i quickly locked all of the doors and called the police. •

the story above was just a small part of the things i endured from an ex boyfriend. and that was after we had broke up... and after he broke into my house. i was terrified and i feared for my life. things had escalated more and more in the relationship so much
column2: that i honestly thought that that was it. that my time had come. i thank the lord that it wasn’t worse. •

column1: 194790;instagram;2019-01-29 03:23:46;FALSE;"#periodcon this weekend exceeded all of my expectations. all year long
column2: my @periodmovement team works tirelessly to support our 250+ chapters worldwide the best that we can — texting and calling with them whenever we can to learn more about their stories and work on the ground. then
column4: we get to meet them in person
column5: and bring our dream of creating community in the #menstrualmovement to life.

column1: @sharonamckee and i have been planning this event for a few months
column2: and it has consumed the majority of my work
column4: and personal life…but it was completely worth it. seeing the smiles on the faces of youth activists and allies during the event
column5: telling stories and learning from each other
column6: furiously taking notes during our panels and speeches
column7: and their sharing with me how much @periodmovement has meant to them in igniting their own changemaking potential…makes me feel like the luckiest gal on the planet.

column2: thank you. thank you to the period team
column3: thank you to our speakers and sponsors
column5: thank you to the 270 of you who joined us for our second-ever #periodcon. y’all changed my life
column6: and i can’t wait to get back to work to plan our next moves with this movement. but first

column1: taking on responsibility for stuff that’s not yours to own is so incredibly common with trauma.
so often i see people in my office blaming themselves for things beyond their control. this happens because the perpetrator or larger social group directly or indirectly communicates they’re at fault
column2: or because the illusion that we have or had control is comforting... because now i can make sure it doesn’t happen again.

column1: the truth is adults with their fully developed brains & their
column3: years of experience expect things of themselves that were beyond their developmental level
column4: weren’t something they ever knew about at the time
column5: or expect themselves to have done something that’s easy to say in the therapy room
column6: but in reality their physiology took over (see previous post on the hand model of the brain).

column1: the truth is we have less control than we think & that’s hard to sit with. 🤨
in therapy & other healing arts we learn what we do & do not have control over. this task is possible & empowering. 😎

column1: 194997;instagram;2019-01-29 12:08:21;FALSE;survivor|this is for that little boy living in the shame of being sexually abused. this is for the women to afraid to seek help. for the little girl seeking direction after being raped but instead she is silenced in fear of being shamed. this is for anyone who has kept the pain & guilt bottled up inside.... this is your day!! for women who feel their bodies have betrayed them. that deal with the everyday doctor appointments while facing infertility decisions. being poked and prodded but still keeping a smile on your face. the ones silently suffering in pain. i understand you
column2: i see you...i am you. i was sexually abused from the age of 5-11 years old. i blamed myself and felt guilty about what happened to me. i also went through 8 years of infertility and spiraled into a deep depression as woman! but on today i have taken back my joy & my peace. i share layers of my journey to encourage others to never give up. you do not have to live in shame. what was done to you was not your fault. you are not alone. speak your truth. as you speak it
